The Internet Wants to be Open
It shouldn=E2=80=99t be surprising that the internet is run by large, centr=
alized companies today. Honestly, our fault.=C2=A0
The early internet, from the 1980s to the early 2000s, was largely open and=
 decentralized. It was built on top of a series of open protocols that anyo=
ne could build directly on top of, like HTTP for websites, SMTP for email, =
SMS for messaging, IRC for chat, and FTP for file transfer. The benefit was=
 that these protocols were generally agreed upon and not subject to change;=
 I could build a website on HTTP and if people had my website address, they=
 could go directly to my site, not intermediated by anyone else.=C2=A0
But there were some major challenges, which I covered in The Value Chain of=
 the Open Metaverse [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEtuxCAMQE8z7BIBg=
TQsWHTTa0R8nASVQMRn0ty-zERqJQySLfPsZ1SBNaZLHjEX9Lrmch0gA5zZQymQUM2QZmclGek0=
