 in value for themselves</strong>.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; fon=
t-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Not Boring Capital inv=
ested in this round and I couldn&#8217;t be more pumped. Replit embodies so=
 many of the themes and ideas that we talk about in Not Boring -- composabi=
lity, decentralization, disruptive innovation, the compounding power of you=
ng users, web3, and more -- and it&#8217;s building a future I want to see =
exist.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 2=
6px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">To understand the company&#8217;s enormous potenti=
al requires projecting the course of each of those themes forward and where=
 they might interact, and then weaving together those different strands int=
o one coherent narrative. Honestly, it&#8217;s been one of the hardest piec=
es for me to write because each thread I pull opens up new paths for explor=
ation, a new &#8220;most exciting thing&#8221; to elucidate.&nbsp;</p><p st=
yle=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em =
0;">So maybe we fast-forward to the end for a second.<strong>&nbsp;</strong=
></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 1em 0;"><strong>Imagine this</strong>: a world in which anyone, anywh=
ere can learn to code, snap together composable services on top of a shared=
 data and compute layer to build products, and monetize those products inst=
antly and continuously, all in the same place. Where everyone can manipulat=
e code like we manipulate words, creating as much richness and novelty in t=
he programs we use as in the books and essays we read.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D=
"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">We=
&#8217;re going to go down a winding path to get to that world, and I hope =
